---
import Heading from "@components/Heading.astro";
import HeadingLarge from "@components/HeadingLarge.astro";
import Text from "@components/Text.astro";
import View from "@components/View.astro";
import Group from "@components/Group.astro";
import { Layout } from "@layouts";
import Image from "@components/Image.astro";
import HeadingSmall from "@components/HeadingSmall.astro";
---

<Layout
  title="Facebook | Jonathon Toon | Software Designer, Product Leader"
  description="Jonathon Toon is a versatile software designer and product leader based in Aotearoa New Zealand."
  keywords="design, software, product, fractional, leadership, new zealand, aotearoa, technology, typescript, start ups, engineering, mentorship, coaching, adplist"
  twitterHandle="@jonathontoon"
  canonicalUrl="https://www.jonathontoon.com/"
  ogImage="/images/og-image.png"
>
  <Group>
    <HeadingLarge class="px-2">Facebook</HeadingLarge>
    <Text class="px-2">
      While no one needs an introduction to Facebook, I was at the company
      during a time that few got to experience. In 2012 the company had just
      passed it's IPO. The stakes were high, as was the energy to innovate and
      grow. I joined as a Product Designer, moving to the United States from New
      Zealand for my first full-time role.
    </Text>
    <Text class="px-2">
      Despite being on the cusp of serving over 1 billion monthly active users,
      Facebook's design team was still under 40 people. Small enough to fit in
      to a conference room. This meant not only did I have an opportunity to
      still make a significant impact, but was able to receive mentorship from
      some of the greatest in the industry.
    </Text>
    <!-- working across
      Photos and Messenger teams to improve how nearly one billion people shared
      and connected. My work increased photo posts by 2%, doubled average photos
      per post, and helped launch voice calling to 300 million users. -->
  </Group>
  <Group>
    <View class="px-2">
      <View class="h-px w-full bg-stone-200 dark:bg-stone-700" />
    </View>
  </Group>
  <Group>
    <Heading class="px-2">Photos Team</Heading>
    <HeadingSmall class="px-2">Simple Picker</HeadingSmall>
    <Text class="px-2">
      Facebook's photo selection frustrated users with algorithmic ordering and
      complex editing tools. Our research revealed that folks wanted to share
      candid moments in a chosen order, quickly. Not with neatly composed
      filters and heavy editing. That was what Instagram was for.
    </Text>
    <Text class="px-2">
      Based on these insights, I designed Simple Picker.
    </Text>
    <Text class="px-2">
      Simple Picker let users select multiple photos quickly, in their preferred
      order, with minimal distractions. It worked seamlessly, adapting to each
      platform's conventions while maintaining a consistent experience. One
      could still access simplified tools, but through an non-instrusive
      long-press (now an industry standard).
    </Text>
  </Group>
  <Group>
    <Image
      src="/images/work/facebook-simple-picker-ios.png"
      alt="Streamlined photo selection experience with batch upload capabilities."
      class="w-full rounded-xl bg-stone-200 dark:bg-stone-800"
      lightbox={true}
    />
    <Image
      src="/images/work/facebook-simple-picker-android.png"
      alt="Cross-platform photo picker maintaining iOS design consistency on Android."
      class="w-full rounded-xl bg-stone-200 dark:bg-stone-800"
      lightbox={true}
    />
  </Group>
  <Group>
    <Text class="px-2">
      After it's launch Simple Picker delivered strong results with photo posts
      increasing by 2%. Additionally average photos per post doubled, while
      revenue-impacting engagement lifted a meaningful amount.
    </Text>
  </Group>
  <Group>
    <HeadingSmall class="px-2">Composer</HeadingSmall>
    <Text class="px-2">
      Building on a weekend prototype from our Design Manager, I created a
      design that integrated Simple Picker into the composer, so users could
      select and share photos without ever leaving their posting flow. Turning a
      multi-step process into an even simpler experience.
    </Text>
    <Text class="px-2">
      Users also could now see their photos clearly with larger previews that
      preserved the original aspect ratios, making photo selection feel more
      engaging and eliminating the guesswork of tiny thumbnails.
    </Text>
  </Group>
  <Group>
    <Image
      src="/images/work/facebook-composer-ios.png"
      alt="Streamlined photo selection experience with batch upload capabilities."
      class="w-full rounded-xl bg-stone-200 dark:bg-stone-800"
      lightbox={true}
    />
  </Group>
  <Group>
    <HeadingSmall class="px-2">Shared Albums</HeadingSmall>
    <Text class="px-2">
      Born from several hackathon efforts, Shared Albums became a major focus
      for the Photos team. Facebook had lost significant ground in photo
      sharing, with many users not seeing it as a place to preserve memories.
    </Text>
    <Text class="px-2">
      I designed the collaborative album experience for Android, enabling
      families and friends to build shared memories from weddings, vacations,
      and gatherings. Everyone could contribute photos from their own devices,
      creating rich, complete albums that no single person could capture alone.
    </Text>
  </Group>
  <Group>
    <Image
      src="/images/work/facebook-shared-albums-android.png"
      alt="Collaborative photo sharing with granular privacy controls."
      class="w-full rounded-xl bg-stone-200 dark:bg-stone-800"
      lightbox={true}
    />
  </Group>
  <Group>
    <Text class="px-2">
      The feature drove millions of users to create shared memories from
      weddings, vacations, and family gatherings, helping Facebook compete with
      Google and Dropbox in photo sharing.
    </Text>
  </Group>
  <Group>
    <HeadingSmall class="px-2">Feed Tagging</HeadingSmall>
    <Text class="px-2">
      We tested several custom interfaces to help users identify untagged faces
      in their photos, but found the simplest approach worked best: leveraging
      existing behaviors rather than creating new ones.
    </Text>
    <Text class="px-2">
      Since people naturally revisited their posts after sharing, I designed a
      gentle prompt that helped them identify untagged friends with a single
      tap. This eliminated the hassle of manually searching through photos
      later, increasing tags by 10% while making the tagging process feel
      effortless.
    </Text>
  </Group>
  <Group>
    <Image
      src="/images/work/facebook-feed-tagging.png"
      alt="Enhanced feed tagging improving user engagement and content discovery."
      class="w-full rounded-xl bg-stone-200 dark:bg-stone-800"
      lightbox={true}
    />
  </Group>
  <Group>
    <View class="px-2">
      <View class="h-px w-full bg-stone-200 dark:bg-stone-700" />
    </View>
  </Group>
  <Group>
    <Heading class="px-2">Messenger Team</Heading>
    <HeadingSmall class="px-2">Voice Calling</HeadingSmall>
    <Text class="px-2">
      Following Messenger's separation from the main Facebook app in 2012, we
      believed voice calling was essential to help users stay connected. It also
      helped us compete with Skype (who held 30% market share) while expanding
      into emerging markets where voice calls were more common than text
      messaging.
    </Text>
  </Group>
  <Group>
    <Image
      src="/images/work/facebook-voice-calling.png"
      alt="Voice calling redesign with improved audio controls and call quality indicators."
      class="w-full rounded-xl bg-stone-200 dark:bg-stone-800"
      lightbox={true}
    />
  </Group>
  <Group>
    <Text class="px-2">
      We designed and shipped the first version for iOS in just four weeks.
      Users could now make crystal-clear voice calls with confidence, seeing
      real-time quality indicators and using intuitive controls. Multi-tasking
      support meant people could browse other conversations or apps without
      dropping calls, making voice communication feel natural within Messenger.
    </Text>
    <Text class="px-2">
      Voice calling eventually grew to 300 million users, becoming one of
      Messenger's most popular features and helping Facebook compete with
      established voice platforms.
    </Text>
  </Group>
</Layout>
